  "text": "The average time required to synchronize frontend and backend processes using spin-locks is 2.5 μsec and is orders of magnitude faster than the primitive than based on virtio (1791 μsec). This big difference makes the mixed approach described in Section IV-B an interesting enhancement to consider as a next step. In both cases, measurements include the system call overhead used to measure the time elapsed. In order to quantify the overhead that this RDMA solution introduces with respect to a native RDMA execution, the micro-benchmarks object of this work [CITATION_1] have been used to measure throughput and latency performance. In [CITATION_2] the experimental hardware was based on a cluster with Intel Xeon nodes connected through the Mellanox ConnectX-3 VPI 56Gb/s FDR Infiniband RNICs. The HyV virtualization framework showed latency and throughput values similar to a native execution, with message sizes of 4B and 16KB and on the latency test with 1B and 64KB on the throughput. Using HyV, the guest system was able to handle the network's card resources, e.g., the completion poll queues, from the guest process without any hypervisor or OS involvement.",
